In the heyday. I remember when they said we had 50% of the US smartphone market share. But the platform was actually built on Java, not Python. Python was something afterwards. Actually, my co-founder is the Python programmer. And I picked up Python after we started working together.

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:23.880
Yeah, cool.

00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:27.540
You got any fun stories from your time at BlackBerry?

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:28.320
Did you enjoy it?

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:28.880
How long were you there?

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:31.580
I was there as an intern only.

00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:36.000
Spent about 16 to 20 months of internships.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:39.180
At the time, I was, I think, in my third year of school.

00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:45.760
And we were just working on these little Java apps for the smartphones

00:01:46.939 --> 00:01:49.240
and just making sure everything was working.

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:55.080
The cool thing is when you work at a company that's making devices, devices have a very

00:01:55.250 --> 00:01:56.800
long development cycle.

00:01:57.560 --> 00:02:02.700
So imagine, for example, you worked at Apple today, like the iPhone, what, 15, whichever

