But it was really cool to know you're on the last thing.

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:23.700
And you couldn't lose it in a bar or anything like that, right?

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:25.340
You remember those stories, right?

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:26.320
Yes, exactly.

00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:27.240
A few times.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.380
Somebody got a hold of a lost phone and it was sold

00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:33.520
and there was all sorts of drama.

00:02:33.630 --> 00:02:34.260
It was a big deal.

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:35.120
Oh, yeah.

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:40.460
That was around an iPhone 4, 3, 4, 5 sort of time frame.

00:02:41.260 --> 00:02:41.580
That's right.

00:02:41.770 --> 00:02:43.360
Yeah, I remember that very clearly.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.280
So you didn't want to be that.

00:02:45.290 --> 00:02:46.900
You wanted to make sure you hung on to it.

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:47.300
Oh, yeah.

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:48.060
No, you can't.

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:52.620
Yeah, I think working for a company like that would have been awesome,

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:53.560
at least in the heyday.

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:59.520
You know, it's cool to work for a tech company that's got a lot of wind

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:02.060
that it's back and a lot of people using it.

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:03.320
It's kind of neat.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:05.140
It was very fun.

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:06.680
I was very happy.

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:10.040
We had a lot of other interns that they hired at the time.

00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:13.100
So you just had a blast working there over the summers.

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:15.820
Yeah, a lot of excited people to do stuff.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:16.540
Excellent.

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:21.120
And so then you picked up Python,

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:23.540
I guess when you started this project, is that right?

00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:25.640
- Just a little bit before.

00:03:26.040 --> 00:03:31.180
So when we started our startup, this was back in 2020.

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:36.160
My co-founder had been using Python.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.640
He did a master's degree, computer science,

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:43.200
focused on machine learning actually.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:45.920
And so, you know, in that field,

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.140
Python is really the main language you use.

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:49.920
Yeah, it is.

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:51.800
And so he was very familiar with it.

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:56.820
And so he set our stack basically to be a Python backend.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:04.380
And then just through that process, just looking at things and designing features,

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:06.900
we just all got involved with Python.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.440
So it kind of just became the same.

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:13.340
And this is actually the reason why we're working on a Python builder

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:15.960
is we're kind of building a product for ourselves.

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:18.540
to something where it fits our own needs,

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:20.859
that works with our mental models.

00:04:21.819 --> 00:04:23.240
So that's pretty much it.

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:29.740
So today I spend a lot of time building apps with DropBase,

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:33.780
so internal tools, and that's most of the app building I do now.

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:37.220
So building demos, testing the product,

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:38.740
making sure everything is working,

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:41.340
and then just finding other ways

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:43.900
to make the developer experience more convenient.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:52.920
It seems like something you could really take care of a bunch of internal automation type of apps.

00:04:53.440 --> 00:05:01.700
You don't have to create full-on web apps to secretize this data or to get that dashboard or whatever, right?

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.620
Just fire up your own platform and point at your data sources.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:06.680
That's right, yeah.

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:14.800
So the big difference with other frameworks is that you're going to use these frameworks to build your customer-facing applications.

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:21.080
And customers have very high expectations about what they need.

00:05:22.340 --> 00:05:25.100
Interactions sometimes make a big difference for them.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:30.420
UI components, the way models come up, it's all part of the experience.

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:35.080
And so for that, you really need a lot of extra components complexity.

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:41.600
For internal tools, it's not to say that internal users don't have high expectations,

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:47.200
But the kinds of things that you do with those tools tend to be very, very similar.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:50.180
You search for data.

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:54.800
You get context about that.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:57.300
So, for example, you search for a transaction or for a user.

00:05:57.740 --> 00:06:01.880
You get some more context to make sure that that's the user or the transaction that you want to act on.

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:03.380
And then you just act on it, right?

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:08.660
Like you trigger an action on that item or that resource or that person.

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:12.740
And so, you know, it helps you simplify the kind of things you need.

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:19.460
And so for that, having a framework, a builder to make this happen is super convenient.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:31.260
So the subtitle catchphrase of DropBase is build internal web apps with just Python, which is awesome.

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:43.060
And when I think of internal web apps, or even traditionally, if you look back a ways, there was VB6 and Windows Forms and those types of things that were kind of playing the same role.

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:46.640
So same basic idea.

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:51.780
There was a lot of people who referred to that as forms over data.

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:59.720
kind of the, not quite a negative term, but kind of like we're sort of doing the same

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:04.920
basic architecture over and over, but it's a different problem every time. And so we kind

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:11.080
of got to write code, create these projects from scratch every time, but they're the kind of same

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:16.520
kind of thing. And so, you know, I think that's partly why VB6 with its kind of visual drag and

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:21.240
droppy experience became real popular because you could drag a table on there and drag a data source,

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:26.560
bind it to that and make a button click when somebody touches this thing. And that didn't

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:33.880
create something that would rival say Airbnb.com or where you were these really dynamic design

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:42.260
sites, but that's not what they need. The company says, look, we need this week. I need our sales

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:48.819
people to be able to answer this question and make this change. That's what we need you to build this

00:07:48.840 --> 00:07:53.060
And if it's from scratch every time, that's a ton of rework.

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:56.940
- Absolutely. It's a lot of work.

00:07:57.540 --> 00:07:59.920
It's funny you mentioned the forms over data.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:04.100
It is true that a lot of the, well,

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:05.680
if you take it at a very high level,

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:08.160
all apps are forms over data.

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:09.620
- In some sense, yeah.

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:16.240
- Or all SaaS apps are forms over a database in some sense.

00:08:17.180 --> 00:08:27.160
And then you start here also about the similar things with, you've heard about the GPT wrappers, right?

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:36.700
It's the same concept where it's like an oversimplification of what's happening, but at the same time, it is kind of core to what's happening.

00:08:37.780 --> 00:08:41.219
And for internal tooling, at least, is exactly what you need.

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:43.479
Forms over data, but very quickly.

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:51.060
So that developers don't have to spend a lot of time basically doing the same things over and over again.

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:55.380
You want to make their lives easier to support their internal users.

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:58.160
So people in customer support and operations.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.900
And I think sometimes even supporting other engineers as well.

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:10.380
Yeah, and it's not that people in companies don't have expectations of nice apps and nice interactions.

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:14.600
It's just that it's more utilitarian.

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:27.160
You know, like so many of these big enterprises, when you kind of think of them, maybe the right way to think of them is there's a massive Postgres or Microsoft SQL server at the center.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:38.020
And it almost connects the business divisions, like the sales team and the marketing team and the product team and all that.

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:51.800
And if you can get into the database and answer questions, expose data, expose relationships, put a UI to some aspect of that, you're really right at the heart of the company in some sense.

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:55.740
Yeah, it's definitely about effectiveness.

00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:21.060
So one way we think about what these kinds of tools should do is you have to enable developers to very quickly build apps that have maximal value, that lets you get the job done as effectively as possible, but also that's easy to use for the end user.

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:28.600
So, you know, if it's like a business operator or someone in the operations team, they also need to be able to learn quickly how to use it and trigger actions.

00:10:29.420 --> 00:10:36.160
And so we call that sort of effectiveness of the apps, some sort of effectiveness score.

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:36.980
Yeah.

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:38.860
And it just combines these components.

00:10:40.090 --> 00:10:49.980
And that's really the, like, if you can get to the essence of it and create a framework or a tool builder that maximizes for that, I think you're in a really good place.

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:52.700
This is something we're trying to do with DropBase.

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:55.780
The components are simple.

00:10:56.840 --> 00:11:01.820
The kinds of apps that you can build look roughly the same, but they look really nice.

00:11:02.060 --> 00:11:04.660
And they're also quite simple to understand.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:11.600
They're modeled after spreadsheets in a way where you have sort of data grid or table in the middle.

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:13.920
And then there's a sidebar from where you can trigger actions.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:33.260
And this ties back to this concept of when you ask people in operations what they do, like sales, marketing, business operations, essentially it ties back to the previous comments, which was you search for something, you get context about it, and you trigger action.

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:42.540
And so the way we translated that insight about what people just end up doing over and over again, we said, well, then you really just need some sort of search bar.

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:51.400
You need a grid and you need a sidebar with some buttons or some other drop downs and other components.

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:56.000
And then you realize, okay, this is kind of what stretches I've been trying to do for a long time.

00:11:56.720 --> 00:11:57.200
Yeah, that's true.

00:11:57.920 --> 00:11:59.460
People do like oddly connect.

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:05.320
Yeah, people do oddly connect Excel to like external data sources and all sorts of weird things as well.

00:12:05.680 --> 00:12:05.820
Yeah.

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:08.360
Or write VBA that makes some change.

00:12:08.360 --> 00:12:09.940
They probably should just not be doing that.

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:14.180
Yeah, there's a lot of this. It's actually a big use case.

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:17.780
One of our previous product, we actually did exactly that.

00:12:18.740 --> 00:12:29.300
So we let you connect any database source to your Google Sheets and just kind of run that on a schedule.

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:39.700
Right. So you'd imagine in a business setting, you have sort of these like weekly, daily reports that analysts end up working on.

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:44.760
And what you want is for the data to be fresh, up to date.

00:12:45.970 --> 00:13:06.460
And so people just wanted a way to on at 7:00 AM, 8:00 AM on Monday morning, basically automatically pull data from a database, load it up to your spreadsheet, and then all your tables and calculations, which is sort of update because they're referencing a tab, a sheet basically that has fresh data.

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:09.840
And that helps people solve problems.

00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:12.620
And so it's very interesting, the evolution of all these tools.

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:15.260
Yeah, it is really interesting.

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:20.220
Maybe one of the big differences is the interactivity here

00:13:21.839 --> 00:13:24.220
versus what you might do in that story, right?

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:26.080
That's right.

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:28.220
So that's read-only, really.

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:31.860
And then here, what we're doing is letting you trigger actions,

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:35.800
perform actions, basically outside the app.

00:13:35.860 --> 00:13:42.420
So you might call an API or you might trigger an internal endpoint or just some triggers

00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:43.220
matching in the UI.

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:44.140
Yeah.

00:13:45.300 --> 00:13:49.040
So I think we'll get to this more later, but I want to maybe touch on it since there's

00:13:49.040 --> 00:13:49.520
a good question.

00:13:49.660 --> 00:13:52.860
Also, it might be a question a lot of people have.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:55.560
So what's the pricing model for this, right?

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:59.660
And basically, more broadly, what is the business model around here?

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:05.240
Luis says, already amazed by it, would like to compare it.

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:08.720
First thought, there's nothing like this available in open source.

00:14:09.150 --> 00:14:10.040
So very neat.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:12.360
Yeah.

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:13.920
So interesting.

00:14:15.100 --> 00:14:24.680
So the business model is we're going to sell the product on a per user per month basis.

00:14:24.860 --> 00:14:26.580
So it's a B2B SaaS product.

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:32.299
Now, developers need to be able to play around with products

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:35.700
before they can decide whether that's something they want.

00:14:36.030 --> 00:14:41.620
And so we have a sort of a free version of the product

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:46.240
that you can set up locally, like in your own machine,

00:14:46.330 --> 00:14:48.840
or you can just put it up on an EC2,

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:51.140
and you can just build apps for yourself.

00:14:51.350 --> 00:14:55.180
Like if you want to automate personal tasks,

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:56.840
you can totally use this for it.

00:14:57.940 --> 00:15:02.280
And then the way that we, in a way, layer the pricing

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:05.260
It's like if you need very complex permission systems,

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:09.220
so like you build an app and you want it accessible by this person,

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:11.640
by person A, but not person B,

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:14.400
then you'll need very granular permission systems.

00:15:14.600 --> 00:15:18.320
And so that's an indicator that you're probably like a corporate user,

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:19.180
you're a business user.

00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:21.980
And so we do the pricing based on that.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:24.640
Cool. Yeah.

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:29.860
So there's an open – the source is open, at least.

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:31.440
People can go and check it out, right?

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:34.820
Let me clarify that. So you can self-host it.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:35.640
Yes.

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:40.180
And you can look at the repo.

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:46.840
Behind the scenes, it's a Docker image that you set.

00:15:47.110 --> 00:15:51.600
So the code for drawbase is not immediately,

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:54.760
you can't just browse it through the file system,

00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:58.520
but the code is basically sitting in your machine

00:15:58.610 --> 00:15:59.660
when you set this up locally.

00:16:00.520 --> 00:16:05.400
Now, the difference here is if you look at the directory where you have the workspace,

00:16:06.430 --> 00:16:14.060
so the workspace directory is where all of your apps, all your apps files would be generated

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:15.480
as you build the apps.

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:16.580
Okay.

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:22.180
And so that's really nice because you can essentially version control this from day one.

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:28.180
You can build apps, you can check it in GitHub, and then you can just keep your code, you can

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:28.600
version it.

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:31.540
And so it's really, it's not open source.

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:34.280
It's clarified that, but you can self-host it.

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:35.460
Okay.

00:16:36.210 --> 00:16:37.040
So, yeah, right.

00:16:37.050 --> 00:16:39.040
So you've got, it's on GitHub,

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:46.360
but the licensing is really not like just straight up GPL open source.

00:16:47.220 --> 00:16:47.580
That's right.

00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:47.800
Right.

00:16:47.980 --> 00:16:48.280
That's correct.

00:16:48.420 --> 00:16:48.520
Okay.

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:48.800
Yes.

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:52.800
And it's on GitHub because you need to, you need to clone,

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:57.620
you do need to clone the repo and then you need to set it out and install it.

00:16:57.880 --> 00:16:58.020
Yeah.

00:16:58.540 --> 00:16:58.620
Yeah.

00:16:58.740 --> 00:17:02.240
Yeah, so the free tier doesn't allow self-hosting,

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:04.560
but if you pay for one of the versions,

00:17:05.990 --> 00:17:07.480
then it does have a self-hosting option.

00:17:08.120 --> 00:17:10.040
So just to wrap this up on the price,

00:17:10.420 --> 00:17:13.020
when you say it's $10 per user per month,

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:17.060
is that per person that makes the project,

